#Step 1: Get the Tools (One-Time Setup)
  Install Flutter: The "Engine" that runs your app.
  Install VS Code: my "Writing Pad" where I type the code.
  Install Android Studio: Just so my laptop can "talk" to Android phones.
  Install Xcode: (for Mac) So my laptop can "talk" to iPhones.

#Step 2: Create the Project (The Skeleton)
  Type: flutter create my_auc_app
  The Result: get one folder with everything inside.
  The lib folder: write the code here.

#Step 3: Write the Code (The "Once" Rule)
  Only write the code once.
  Open the file called main.dart.
  Type in Dart: "Make a button that says 'Find Room'."
  The Result: That button is now ready for both Android and iPhone.

#Step 4: See it on the Phone (Testing)
  Android: Plug in an Android phone and press "Play" in VS Code. The app appears.
  iPhone: Plug in an iPhone and press "Play." The same app appears.
  Change something: If I change the button to Green and hit "Save," it changes on both phones instantly (Hot Reload).

#Step 5: The "Final Gift" (Building)
  When the project is finished, just turn the code into a file I can share.
  For Android: You get an .APK file.
  For iPhone: You get an .IPA file.
